{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958042501/0246.xml":{"full_text":"Anti-Recession Programs\nSlowed Up by Eisenhower\nNation Is Near\nDepression, Says\nPresident Meany\nPrograms to check the still\ndeepening recession ground to i\na near halt as Pres. Eisen-1\nhower smashed with his veto,\npower against public works\nand maintained total opposition\nto early tax reduction.\ni\nAs Congress returned from its,\nEaster recess. AFL-CIO Pres\nGeorge Meany warned that the\ncountry \u201cstands on the brink of\ndepression\" and \u201cinevitably ad\nditional millions will soon join\nthe ranks of the unemployed\u201d1\nunless there is \u201cbolder action\u201d to\ncheck the business slump\nCounting the totally unem\nployed and those on part-time\nlayoffs, \u201cnearly 9.5 percent of\nour labor force is jobless\" and\n\u201cevery important (economic)\nindicator continues to point\ndownward,\" Meany said in\nidentical letters to all mem\nbers.\nBut Eisenhower greeted Con\ngress with a veto of the $1 7 bil-1\nlion rivers-and-harbors bill. and\nRepublicans in the Senate fought\nto check and to slice the money\nauthorization of the Fulbright:\ncommunity facilities bill from.\n$1 billion to $500 million\nFacilities Bill Passes\ni\ni\ni\nThe facilities bill, which would\nauthorize loans for city water\nand sewer systems and similar\nlocal public works, went through\nbut only after GOP direct and\nflank attacks had been beaten\noff\nOnly 10 Republicans broke\nparty lines to oppose the effort\nto reduce the funds to $500 mil-1\nlion The bill already had been\nslashed in committee from $2\nbillion originally proposed A\nmajority of Republicans also\nsupported an amendment to\ndamage the bill by tying its mon-l\ney to school construction, which\nthey knew would defeat it in\nthe House\no n\nRepublican opposition\nthe floor defeated an amend\nl\nr\nment to hold the interest rates\non such loans to 3 percent.\nBy almost a straight party\nline division, GOP leaders suc\nceeded in maintaining the 3.5\npercent interest rate they had\nforced into the bill in commit\ntee.\nSen. Lyndon Johnson (D\nTex.). Democratic floor leader,\nannounced flatly that he would\nnot seek a vote on attempting\nto override Eisenhower\u2019s pre\nEaster veto of the farm bill\nfreezing price supports at pres\nent levels for one year Without\nindications of Republican sup\nport in a Senate divided only 49\nto 47 on party lines, he said, an\neffort to get the required two\nthirds vote to override would be\nfutile.\nGOP Support Needed i\nA decision on an attempt to\noverride the rivers-and-harbors\nveto also would depend on a\n\u201ccanvass\" of possible Republi\ncan support, he said\nSen. William F. Knowland\n(R Calif.), GOP floor leader,\ndenied that Republicans were\nthrowing roadblocks at the\nDemocratic anti-recession pro\ngram, but the effect of the\nrivers-and-harbor veto and the\nGOP assault on the Fulbright\nmeasure added up to a clear\nwarning that Eisenhower\nwould make full use of his\npower to halt measures that he\nfelt went \u201ctoo far.\u201d\nThe President signed the mea\nsure. but the \"planted\u201d reports\nof the veto threat cast a chill\nover Democratic planning for\nfuture legislation. The White\nHouse had fought the Gore meas\nure in committee, seeking to cut\nthe authorization as too big.\nOn tax reduction, Republi- i\ncans exploited to the full ex-\ntent the \u201cgentlemen's agree\nment\u201d still operating between\nthe Treasury Dept, and House\nDemocratic leaders that neith-\ner side will propose tax cuts\nwithout advance warning to\nthe other\nChances appeared\ngood for\nHouse Ways and Means Com\nmittee approval of a\ncompro\nIke Urges Public\nTo Hunt Bargains\nCommenting that \u201cmany\npeople\u201d are holding off au\ntomobile purchases in the\nhope of an excise tax cut,\na reporter asked Pres. Ei\nsenhower whether he\nthought any such cut\nshould be \u201cretroactive.\u201d\nThe President declined\nat his news conference to\nanswer directly but said\nthere is a \u201cgreat field of ex\npansion of business by bet\nter salesmanship.\u201d\n\u201cWe have got great sav\nI believe\nings,\u201d he said.\nthat we have got to offer\nthings in a better-packaged\nway, we\u2019ve got to do better\nadvertising, and above all\nthings let the public buy\nwhen they think they are\ngetting a bargain and not\nworrying about what is\ngoing to be the possible\nfuture of some possible fu\nture action.\u201d\nmise bill extending unemploy\nment insurance to assist the\n45,000 jobless workers now\nexhausting their benefits each\nweek under state laws.\nBut the committee turned\ndown an effort by Rep. Eugene\nJ. Keogh (D-N. Y.) to attach the\nKennedy-McCarthy bill that\nwould push jobless benefits up\nward by establishing new federal\nstandards creating basic mini\nmums on payment, eligibility\nand duration.\nMeany\u2019s letter to members\nnt Congress reminded them\nthat on Mar. 11 he had public\nly warned the country would\nbe \u201cin serious trouble\u201d unless\nthe month's unemployment\nfigures showed \u201ca seasonal\ndrop of at least 200,000 jobs.\u201d\nInstead of a drop there was an\n\u201cactual increase,\u201d he pointed\nout.\n\u201cMore than 5.2 million\nAmericans are jobless, another\n3.5 million are working less\nthan a full week,\u201d and \u201cthere\n\"Hold On To Your Hat!\"\n1\nK\n2\u2018h\n\u201cY\nAA\nX* k\n\n\nji\nLa\nLt\nT\n\nA:\nA Y..\nYh W\nri\n\ns\n\n\u2022y\nP\n4\nk\n&a\n\n\u2019s.<\ne\nS.\nhs\n\n7**\nB1,\n\n>9\"\n$41\nNie\n4\nk\nt\n\n\u20192\n3.\ny\n\n264\n*t\n8\n\nay\nek\n\nI\n\n<p\n/0\nA\nf\nw\n*4\nwi\ns\n224\n\"h\u2019s\n.A\n44\ny*\nis\n\nwb\nsh\n4s\n.57:\n\nivat\nvobpaakarnGsh\nfcotkboduecienae\n\njpr\nPExt\n27\nfone\nch\n.1,\nwmeecc))\nd\nwh\nL\n\nfeeas\nAA\nats\n\u2014Pseate\nwoirlg\n9 EPE0274\n\n\ney.\n\nar\na\n\n6r.\n\nIsn\u2019t a single ray of sunshine\non the economic scene.\u201d\nHe asked \"swift, meaning\nful action\u201d with \u201cfirst priority\nto relieving the plight of the\nunemployed\u201d through the\nKennedy-McCarthy bill.\n\"A $6 billion to $8 billion\ntax reduction in both personal\nincome and excise taxes could\nbe decisive\u201d in relieving \u201cthe\nplight of the economy Itself,\u201d\nhe said.\nHe also endorsed full-scale\npublic works including school\nconstruction and housing meas\nures, a depressed-areas law and\nimprovements in\nminimum\nwages and social security.\nAuthorized Repair Service for\nNorelco Electric Shavers\nSmall Electric Appliances\nGeneral Repair Equipment\n116 SUMMIT ST. CH 3-1431\nLabor TV To Hear\nWorld Trade Talk\n1\nAccelerated world trade with\nnations such as Russia and the\nCommunist bloc has been sug\ngested as a. possible anti-reces\nsion measure. Blair Bolles, fore\nign affairs analyst, will discuss\nwhether this measure would\nhelp, its possibility, and its ad\nvisability when he appears as\nspecial guest of Peter Zvara on\nthe Voice of Labor this Sunday\nnoon over Channel 13.\nMr. Bolles is thoroughly ac\nquainted with the political and\neconomic phases of international\naffairs A former foreign cor\nrespondent for the Toledo Blade,\nhe is also the author of numerous\nbooks concerning the world\nscene.\nHis most recent book, \u201cThe\nBig Change in Modern Europe\u201d\nhas received wide critical ac\nclaim as a penetrating and ob\njective study of Europe today.\n800900\nCONSUMER DEBT At All-!\ntime Record: At the end of 1957,\nnonfarm persons owed about\n$176,000,000,000 in debts, an\nalltime high. This was about\nfive times as great as such debt\noutstanding in the U. S. at the\nend of 1929; about three times\nas great as that at the end of\n1948, and approximately one\nand a half times as great as at\nthe close of 1953. Thus, the U. S.\neconomy has entered a recession\nperiod with a debt burden by.\nfar the greatest in its history.\nInstallment debt payments\nalone take about $40,000,000,000\na year out of people\u2019s income,\nwhile mortgage debt payments\ntake $9,400,000,000. Together,\nthese debts require payments\namounting to more than 17 cents\nout of every dollar of personal\nincome after taxes. In 1946, such\npayments took only about 6\ncents and in 1950 about 10 cents.\nA sharp rise in the repossess\nion rate on cars and other dur\nable consumer goods can lead\nto serious consequences. Should\nlarge-scale repossessions force\nthe price of second-hand items\ndown so low that the investment\nin them cannot be recovered,\nI the entire credit structure\nmight collapse.\nI\nFARMERS WORSE OFF: The\nI\nI House Appropriations Commit- 'r\n[tee said on March 28 that the;\nfarmer was much worse off than\nwhen the Eisenhower-N ixon\n\u201cteam took office in 1953. The\nCommittee reported that net in\ncome from farming is at the\nlowest point in 15 years. It said\nalso that the farmer\u2019s share of\neach dollar spent for food has\ndropped steadily since 1952. It\nadded that per capita income\nearned on the farm has dropped\nfrom $702 in 1952 to $684 in\n1957.\nThe Committee expressed dis\nappointment that efforts to com\nbat the recession do not include\nagriculture. \u201cNo proposals are\nbeing made to bolster farm in\ncome at the market place,\u201d it\nsaid.\nEvery worker knows that the\nless money the farmer earns,\nthe less he has to spend for\ngoods and services made and\nfurnished by working men and\nwomen.\nTruman Asks Action\nTo Expand, Economy\nFormer\nPresident\nTruman\ncame back to Washington last,\nweek to preach the doctrine of\nan expanding economy to a fas\ncinated House Banking Commit\ntee.\nTestifying on the recession,1\nTruman remarked scathingly\nthat there seems to be a \u201cstrange\nnotion abroad\u201d that \"full em\nployment and full production\nsomehow would cause an explo\nsion that would blow the econ\nomy apart and end up in a de\npression that would curl your\nhair.\u201d\n\u201cI would not sit in a pool of\neconomic stagnation because of\nsome fear\u2014real or fanciful\u2014\nof inflation somewhere down\nthe road in the future.\u201d\nHe recommended immediate\nincreases in federal spending for\nan \u201cadequate defense\u201d and for:\n\u201cnecessary and vital public pro\ngrams\u201d for housing, education\nand welfare.\nAsks Tax Cut\nHe also recommended a read\njustment of the tax system to\n\u201creduce by $5 billion the amount\nimposed on middle- and low\nincome families\u201d and to recap\nture $3 billion of this by closing\nup \u201cthe most glaring tax loop\nholes and inequitable benefits to\ni\nprivileged groups.\u201d\nIn addition, Truman said, $2\nbillion now being \u201cwasted\u201d in\nhigh interest charges on the na\ntional debt could be \u201csaved\u201d by\n\u201creversing policies that do \u201cal\nmost irreparable damage to our\nwhole economy.\u201d\nSees Departure From Law\nPointing out that \u201cpractically\nevery business analyist\u201d says the\npresent recession is \u201cby far the\nmost serious and dangerous since\nWorld War II,\" Truman charged\nthat the \u201croot of the difficulty\u201d\nis a departure from the \u201cphil\nosophy of maximum employ\nment, production and purchasing\npower set forth in the Employ\nment Act of 1946.\"\nTo match our labor-force\ngrowth of 1 percent and our\nproductivity increase of S per\ncent a year, he said, \u201cour total\nnational product needs to ex\npand by about 4.5 percent a\nyear.\u201d\nThe rate of growth averaged\nabove 4.5 percent for the years\n1947-53, he said, but during\nthe years 1952-57 it slipped to\n2.3 percent.\nOn specific points Truman\nmade the following comments:\nDespite \"claims\u201d from Pres.\nEisenhower that the 1959 budget\nwill show a slight surplus, \"prac\ntically every informed expert ex\npects a deficit between $4 and\n$8 billion.\u201d This estimate was\nnot challenged by committee\nmembers.\nThe deficit is \u201cdue in large\npart to the recession\u201d and the re\ncession in turn is due \u201cto the in\nability of consumers to buy.\u201d\nWhat the consumer lacks \u201cis not\nconfidence but income after\ntaxes.\u201d\nHis own administration had\nnot been \u201centirely successful\u201d in\ndealing with unemployment and\n\u201cwe had an economic recession\nin 1949.\u201d But it was not \"as pro\nlonged and deep\u201d as the current\nslump, and \u2018\u2018one thing we\nlearned was that perhaps we\nshould have acted more vigor\nously than we did.\u201d\nWe should raise defense ex\npenditures, foreign aid and wel\nfare spending now. We should\nincrease domestic i n v e stment\nacross five years to spend $12\nbillion for education and health,\n$2.5 billion for natural resources,\n$2.2 billion for housing and ur\nban redevelopment.\nWe would pay the bill from\ntotal national output raised from\n$434 billion to $600 billion and\nhave a budget representing \"a\nsmaller fraction of total produc\ntion.\u201d\nOn tax cuts, Congress\n\u201cshould be careful not to pass\nout benefits to investors and\nwell-to-do people who if they\nare suffering at all, are suffer\ning only because average fam\nilies do not have enough pur\nchasing power.\u201d\nJ. F. ANDERSON\nCOMPANY, INC.\nResidential and Commercial\nConstruction\nCOMPLETE REMODELING AND\nMODERNIZATION SERVICE\n2852 South\nWA\n3414\nant!\nI\nBe Sure To Phone\nI\nYour Reservations Now\nJames Proctor CH 1-5171\nFrazier Reams Jr. CH 8-6494\n4 $10 Per Plate\no\n17\nja\nThe Party of Progress\nInvites You To\n1\nThe Annual\nYOUNG\n4\n4\nDEMOCRATS BANQUET\nSaturday, May 3rd at 7:30 P.M\nin The Sports Arena\nSee and Hear One of America's\nGreat Young Democrats\n\nI\nHonorable FRANK CHURCH\nDEMOCRATIC SENATOR From IDAHO\nThe Youngest Member of The United States Senate\nThis Message Sponsored By\nLUCAS COUNTY YOUNG DEMOCRATS\nPaul H. Kolby, President\n0\nC","height":"26940","width":"19448"}}
